04338nmm a2200529Ia 9781501717727DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20181998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017177277 a10.7591/97815017177272doi  a(DE-B1597)503407  a(OCoLC)1038475150  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF539.S77 199704a346.7301/61 aStrasser, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLegally Wed :bSame-Sex Marriage and the Constitution /cMark Strasser. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a new preface, Mark Strasser discusses recent developments in the legal battle over same-sex marriages in Hawaii. He anticipates the likely state and nationwide impact of the Hawaii Supreme Court's decision.Mark Strasser examines the issue of same-sex marriage in light of contemporary constitutional and domestic relations law, showing why the usual arguments against recognizing such unions are either weak or irrelevant.The Supreme Court has articulated numerous interests promoted by marriage, all of which apply to same-sex as well as opposite-sex couples. According to Strasser, the argument made most frequently to deny recognition to same-sex unions—that marriage exists to provide a setting for the production and raising of children—is in fact a reason to acknowledge such unions. The claim that marriage is for children biologically related to both parents is refuted in the case law, which treats biological and adopted children as legally indistinguishable. Strasser explains Baehr v. Lewin, the precedent setting case in Hawaii, and addresses the implications of state-by-state decisions to ban or recognize same-sex unions. He analyzes what it would mean to say that a policy violates the Equal Protection or Due Process Clauses of the Constitution, and compares biased polices that target gays and lesbians with those that victimize racial minorities. Strasser argues that the Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) is both unconstitutional and a public policy disaster. It does not give states additional rights with respect to which marriages they need not recognize, Strasser explains, but only with respect which divorces they need not recognize. For example, DOMA seems to allow an individual to avoid a court-imposed duty to support an ex-spouse of the same sex simply by changing his or her domicile. Moreover, Strasser argues, DOMA is an open invitation for states to demand exceptions that will wreak havoc in domestic relations law. In a recent response to conservative arguments about marriage, Legally Wed explicates established and involving legal principles, and shows how invidiously these have been applied to the issues of gay rights in general and same-sex unions in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aGay couplesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aGay couplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aSame-sex marriagezUnited States. 4aGay & Lesbian Studies. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171772740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717727/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles